          "type": "text",
          "text": "✅ **Circuit built successfully!**\n\n### **Wiring Table**\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Pin |\n|---|---|---|\n| 2 | R_a | a (220Ω → seg7.a) |\n| 3 | R_b | a (220Ω → seg7.b) |\n| 4 | R_c | a (220Ω → seg7.c) |\n| 5 | R_d | a (220Ω → seg7.d) |\n| 6 | R_e | a (220Ω → seg7.e) |\n| 7 | R_f | a (220Ω → seg7.f) |\n| 8 | R_g | a (220Ω → seg7.g) |\n| 9 | Button | a (segment pin) |\n| GND | Button | b (pulled low when pressed) |\n| GND | 7-Seg | gnd (common cathode) |\n\n### **How It Works**\n- **Display**: 7-segment shows digits 0–9. Each segment (a–g) is driven through a 220Ω current-limiting resistor from pins 2–8.\n- **Button**: Wired to pin 9 with INPUT_PULLUP. Pressing increments the counter and wraps at 10 (returns to 0).\n- **Debounce**: 50ms software debounce prevents false triggers from switch bounce.\n- **Segment Lookup**: Hardcoded `displayDigit()` function sets the correct segments for each digit 0–9.\n\nThe counter starts at 0 and increments by 1 each time you press the button."
        }
      ]
    }
